Sark(0) prints the current break pos, but when you do sbrk(1024) you change the break pos to 1024 bytes ahead but it\'92ll return the old sark() pos, which is the sbrk(0) in this case, but if you do the following: sbrk(1024) \'97> sbrk(0) it\'92ll move the break pos then you can print the sbrk(0) to make sure its the new pos.\
Sark increments by 4096 bytes, ex: Initial break: 0x100bcc000, after sbrk(4096): Break after: 0x100bcd000, that\'92s because the OS works in a 4096 bytes format, which is also a ASCII system.\
