\f0\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 This is the crucial difference between munmap and typical free: munmap actually tells the OS to revoke the mapping \'97 the virtual address pages are removed from your process's page table. Any access to those addresses after that point is illegal. With glibc's free, the memory often stays mapped (just marked available internally), so reading a freed pointer doesn't immediately crash \'97 it's undefined behaviour that silently works, which is actually more dangerous because bugs hide. munmap makes the bug immediatel\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 y visible.\cf2 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec25 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \outl0\strokewidth0 \
\pard\tx566\tx1133\tx1700\tx2267\tx2834\tx3401\tx3968\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6236\tx6803\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf2 In mmap, if you set the size/lenght to 2 rather that 4096, which is actually a full page, the OS will dedicate a full page for the mmap\'92s 2 bytes request, that\'92s the problem, so the OS will round up to the nearest page. Better explanation:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The OS always maps in multiples of the page size (4096 bytes on x86-64), so even though you asked for 2 bytes, you physically have a full 4096-byte page. This is why allocators that use mmap internally always round up their requests to the nearest page: ex: requesting 17 bytes wastes almost 4079 bytes of a page, so you batch up requests to make full use of each mapping.\cf2 \outl0\strokewidth0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
In mmap, if you set the permissions to PROT_READ then you try to write something you\'92ll get segfault or bus error, that\'92s because you are trying to write on to an area form the virtual memory that you can\'92t write, which explains the bus error perfectly. \
Better explanation:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 You get SIGSEGV the moment you write. The CPU's memory management unit checks the permission bits on the page table entry before every memory access \'97 a write to a read-only page raises a hardware fault which the OS converts to SIGSEGV. This is how the OS enforces memory protection between regions: your code segment (.text) is mapped PROT_READ | PROT_EXEC but not PROT_WRITE, which is why overwriting your own code at runtime also crashes.\outl0\strokewidth0  \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec28 A bus error is a hardware-level fault that occurs when a process attempts to access memory that the CPU cannot physically address, such as accessing an invalid physical address, performing unaligned memory access on strict-architecture systems, or encountering errors with memory-mapped files (e.g., truncating a mapped file while it is in use).\strokec29 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
