\f0\fs28 \cf2 \outl0\strokewidth0 When adding an int is_free data type to it, t\cf0 \outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 he struct grows because the compiler adds padding after int is_free (4 bytes) to align uint32_t magic (also 4 bytes), but since they're the same alignment requirement they actually pack together cleanly. The size grows by 8 bytes total because pointer fields after them require 8-byte alignment, so the compiler may add trailing padding. The exact number depends on your platform. \
 \'97> The important habit is to always set magic in your allocator's extend_heap and always check it at the start of my_free.\cf2 \outl0\strokewidth0 \
\
But then what happens to sizeof(Block) with the magic field?\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 adding the magic field costs you nothing. The original struct had 4 bytes of invisible padding between is_free and next (to keep the pointer 8-byte aligned). The uint32_t magic field is exactly 4 bytes, so it fills that padding slot perfectly and sizeof(Block) stays at 32. This is a good lesson in struct layout \'97 always think about where the compiler is hiding padding before assuming a struct is as compact as it looks.\cf2 \outl0\strokewidth0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\
The ship of two \cf0 \outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 two adjacent blocks in memory:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec32 === Memory Layout ===\
[Block A header]  @ 0x...00  size=64   free=0\
[Block A data  ]  @ 0x...20  (64 bytes for user)\
[Block B header]  @ 0x...60  size=128  free=1\
[Block B data  ]  @ 0x...80  (128 bytes for user)\
\
Offset of B from start of memory: 96 bytes\
= sizeof(Block) + A->size = 32 + 64 = 96\
\cf13 \strokec13 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \strokec2 The pattern is always: [header][----user data----][header][----user data----].... Every header is exactly sizeof(Block) bytes. The user pointer is always header + 1. Recovering the header from a user pointer is always (Block*)ptr - 1. Burn this pattern into your memory \'97 you'll use it constantly in weeks 2 and 3.
